{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639083"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:03:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17762"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17762"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.95,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72376"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10476"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57846"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24521"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72376"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent retrosternal chest pain. The pain tends to occur after large meals or when he lays down. He reports experiencing a sour taste in his mouth and occasional difficulty swallowing. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as an office manager and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no abnormalities on abdominal examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Achalasia","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease","Oesophageal cancer","Para-oesophageal hernia","Peptic ulcer disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms described in the stem are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Egastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterised by heartburn, acid regurgitation, and sometimes dysphagia. The sour taste in the mouth is due to acid reflux, and the difficulty swallowing can occur due to inflammation or irritation of the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with epigastric pain that may be relieved by eating or antacids, but it does not usually cause acid regurgitation or a sour taste in the mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the oesophagus has trouble moving food down into the stomach, leading to dysphagia, but it is not typically associated with acid regurgitation or heartburn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dysphagia and weight loss, but it is less likely in a patient with no significant risk factors and a presentation of intermittent heartburn and acid regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to GORD by allowing stomach acid to move up into the oesophagus, but it is not a diagnosis on its own without the presence of reflux symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is characterised by symptoms such as heartburn, acid regurgitation, and dysphagia.","GORD is a common condition where stomach acid frequently flows back up the oesophagus.","Lifestyle modifications and medications are often effective in managing GORD symptoms."],"references":["Antunes C, Aleem A, Curtis SA. Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722967.","Fox M, Forgacs I. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. BMJ. 2006 Jan 14;332(7533):88-93. doi: 10.1136/bmj.332.7533.88. PMID: 16410582; PMCID: PMC1326932.","Clarrett DM, Hachem C. Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD). Mo Med. 2018 May-Jun;115(3):214-218. PMID: 30228725; PMCID: PMC6140167.","Mousa H, Hassan M. Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2017 Jun;64(3):487-505. doi: 10.1016/j.pcl.2017.01.003. PMID: 28502434; PMCID: PMC6509354."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57846"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17762"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57846"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T10:24:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T10:24:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10476"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72376"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"